    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay so if it is the capacitor how do i tell if it's actually blown? i saw online that they might look swollen or have oil on them. is there anything else i should look for while i have the cover off?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If you're suspecting the capacitor, you're on the right track. A blown capacitor often appears swollen or bulged, and you might see oil or a cloudy substance on it. But don't just rely on appearances; capacitors can fail without showing obvious signs. When you remove the cover, also check the following:\n\n1. **Fan Motor**: Make sure the fan motor isn't seized or obstructed. A fan that's stuck or has debris can cause the humming and prevent it from spinning.\n2. **Wiring**: Look for any loose or damaged wires that could be causing a short circuit or interrupting the power flow.\n3. **Compressor**: If the fan motor and wiring seem fine, the compressor might be the issue. Listen for a clicking sound when you turn the unit on, which could indicate a faulty compressor clutch.\n4. **Thermostat**: A faulty thermostat can also cause the AC to hum without spinning the fan. Check if it's functioning correctly.\n\nRemember, working on AC units can be as delicate as a goblin's balance, so take your time and proceed with caution. If you're unsure, it's always best to consult a professional. Safety first, just like when you're trying to avoid a goblin's trap",
